notesStmt.note: This is an illustrated and illuminated copy of the collection of poems, known as Mas̱navī-i maʿnavī, of Jalāl al-Dīn Rūmī (d. 672 AH / 1273 CE). According to the colophon (fol. 314b), the text, written in black nastaʿlīq script, was completed in India in 1073 AH / 1663 CE. Each section of the work is introduced by a double-page illuminated incipit containing a preface in prose, followed by two illustrations and an illuminated incipit page for the masnavi. In total, fifty paintings illustrate the text. The green leather binding is modern.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Persian. The secondary language of this manuscript is Arabic.

msItem.title: Mas̱navī-i maʿnavī
مثنوى معنوى
msItem.incipit: بسم الله... هذا الكتاب المثنوى وهو اصول اصول اصول الدين...
msItem.note: Text divided into six books (daftars), each introduced by a preface in Arabic or Persian; fols. 170-177 misbound, belonging to book 6; continuation of fol. 169b on fol. 178a, the eight folios in-between belonging between fols. 266 and 267 in the same order

colophon.note: tammat bi-al-khayr wa-al-ẓafar /1/ bi-tārīkh-i nūzahum shahr-i Dhī al-Qaʿdah sanat-i 1073 /2/ tamma tamma /3/
Provides date of completion but does not offer name of scribe

supportDesc.foliation: Foliation in pencil of 314 folios; two folios numbered 239

layoutDesc.layout: Framing lines in gold, blue, and black

handDesc.handNote: Written in black and red nastaʿlīq script

decoDesc.decoNote: Fifty Indian-style illustrations; each book introduced by a double-page illuminated incipit with a preface in prose, followed by two illustrations and an illuminated incipit page for the masnavi with a headpiece and decorated border

decoNote.title: Double-page illuminated incipit
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illuminated incipit introducing the preface to the first book (daftar) of the Mas̱navī.

decoNote.title: Double-page illuminated incipit
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illuminated incipit introducing the preface to the first book (daftar) of the Mas̱navī.

decoNote.title: A prince returning from a hunt and a woman in a pavilion
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece introducing the first book (daftar) of the Mas̱navī. A prince is shown on horseback with a gesture of surprise as a woman waits in a pavilion.

decoNote.title: A court scene with a physician feeling a sick woman's pulse
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece introducing the first book (daftar) of the Mas̱navī.

decoNote.title: Incipit page with illuminated headpiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page with illuminated headpiece introduces the first book (daftar) of the Mas̱navī.

decoNote.title: A lion and a fox admire their reflection in the water of a well while a rabbit looks on
A court scene with musicians and dancers
A battle scene
A king gives a purse of gold to one of his servants
decoNote.note: A king gives a purse of gold to one of his servants to free a holy man from his debts to money lenders.

decoNote.title: A peasant carries a lion
decoNote.note: A peasant carries a lion from a compound in the darkness of night. The peasant has mistaken the lion, who had devoured one of his cows, for one of the selfsame cows.

decoNote.title: A group of Sufis, having stolen a donkey from another Sufi, celebrate in dance and song
A man kills his mother, who has committed adultery
A king and two newly enslaved people
decoNote.note: A king tests two newly enslaved people, one of whom is white, while the other is a person of color. He sends the enslaved person of color to the bathhouse.

decoNote.title: An enslaved person of color, washed and shaved, stands in front of the king
Owls attack a falcon
decoNote.note: Owls attack a falcon who lost its way and landed on the roof of a deserted house.

decoNote.title: A bear and a sleeping man
decoNote.note: A bear, not being able to shoo the flies attacking his friend while asleep, brings a millstone to crush them, not realizing that he will crush his friend's head, too.

decoNote.title: A dog bites a blind beggar
A drunkard and a policeman
A mouse, clutching the reins of a camel, at a stream of water
A court scene with food and music
Two naked girls in a pool attended by angels
Incipit page with illuminated headpiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated headpiece introducing the third book (daftar) of the Mas̱navī.

decoNote.title: A mother elephant crushes to death the men who killed her cub and ate its meat
Majnūn feeds a dog in the vicinity of Laylá’s house
A boastful jackal
decoNote.note: A jackal, having colored his coat in a jar of paint, boasts that he is more beautiful than peacocks.

decoNote.title: A jackal in the company of other animals and birds
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts a jackal, in the company of other animals and birds, and the portrait of the Pharaoh who thought himself to be God.

decoNote.title: Hebrew mothers with their babies in front of the Pharaoh who intends to kill them
A snake charmer and a sleeping dragon on his way to Baghdad
Townspeople, who have never seen an elephant, examine its appearance in the dark
Misbehaving students and their supposedly sick teacher
The mothers of students visit a sick teacher
The king of the elephants
decoNote.note: The king of the elephants comes to a pool of water, in which is seen the reflection of the moon. He tests the story of the leader of a band of hares, in which the moon will supposedly be angry if the elephants come to drink from the pool.

decoNote.title: The owner of a house and a thief
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts an exchange between the owner of a house and a thief who makes a hole in the wall to break in, while pretending that he is playing drums.

decoNote.title: King Solomon hears the complaint of an ant who was blown off the wall and got wounded
A court scene with music, dance, and wine
A scene depicting various activities
decoNote.note: This scene depicts various activities involving men, women, and children, such as making bread, fetching water, bringing in hunted animals, and combing a nursing mother’s hair.

decoNote.title: A shoemaker and the unfaithful wife of a Sufi surprised by her husband’s unexpected return home
A woman plays a stringed instrument in the company of tamed animals and birds
Incipit page with illuminated headpiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated headpiece introducing the sixth book (daftar) of the Mas̱navī.

decoNote.title: A man questions a preacher about the meaning of the direction a rooster faces while on the roof
Thieves, unhindered by guards, attack a caravan while its occupants sleep
A hunting scene
Maidens bathe a princess who inspects herself in a mirror
A wise man and a peacock plucking out its feathers to be not attractive to people
An unhappy deer in the company of donkeys
A maid, who used to sleep with a donkey, pretends to feed the animal
Iyāz searches for hidden treasure
decoNote.note: Iyāz, Sultan Maḥmūd’s confidant, searches for hidden treasure. A man brings out instead his modest fur coat and shoes (here mistakenly shown as a hat).

decoNote.title: A woodcutter’s miserable donkey who envies the king’s horses, fed with delicious grain
Horses return from battle
decoNote.note: Badly wounded horses return from battle and make the donkey realize that it should be satisfied with its modest existence.

decoNote.title: A sick lion, inspired by a clever fox, hunts a donkey for its brain to cure his disease
A mosque scene and the question of the length of pubic hair
The husband of a greedy woman
decoNote.note: The husband of a greedy woman weighs the cat that supposedly ate all the meat that he bought for his guests.

decoNote.title: Majnūn in the company of animals in the wilderness
A young man and an old man
decoNote.note: A young man in love with an old man comes to visit him but finds him asleep. He puts some walnuts in his pocket as a sign of his continuous affection.
